-- India’s Nifty Stock-Index Futures Advance Amid Fund Inflows
-- B y   R a j h k u m a r   K   S h a a w
-- 2013-11-18T03:38:15Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-11-18/india-s-nifty-stock-index-futures-advance-amid-fund-inflows.html
Indian (SENSEX)  stock-index futures climbed,
after the benchmark index rose the most in two weeks on Nov. 14.  SGX CNX  Nifty (NIFTY)  Index futures for November delivery added 0.6
percent to 6,165 at 11:37 a.m. in  Singapore . The underlying CNX
Nifty Index gained 1.1 percent to 6,056.15 on Nov. 14, with
local exchanges shut for a holiday on Nov. 15. The S&P BSE
Sensex increased 1 percent to 20,399.42, ending a seven-day
decline. The  Bank of New York Mellon India ADR Index  of U.S.-
traded shares rose 1.3 percent on Nov. 15.  Asian shares advanced for a third day today after  China 
vowed to carry out the broadest expansion of economic freedoms
since at least the 1990s.  New York  Federal Reserve Bank
President William C. Dudley is scheduled to speak, after Janet
Yellen, the nominee for chairman, said last week she wants to
maintain the central bank’s record stimulus program until the
U.S. economy improves. Foreign investors bought a net $59.2
million of Indian shares on Nov. 12, a 27th day of purchases.  “We expect Indian markets to catch up with the rest of
regional peers after the long weekend,”  Arun Kejriwal , a
director at Kejriwal Research & Investment Pvt., said by phone
today. “Foreign buying has been strong and that’s likely to
continue to some more time given the outlook for tapering by the
U.S. Fed.”  2013 Gain  The Sensex has gained 5 percent this year and trades at
13.4 times projected 12-month profits, compared with MSCI
 Emerging Markets  Index’s 10.6 times.  India ’s economy is struggling to pick up pace, Reserve Bank
of India Governor Raghuram Rajan said in speech in Mumbai on
Nov. 15.  “We need to reduce demand somewhat without having serious
adverse effects on investment and supply,” Rajan said. “This
is a balancing act, which requires the Reserve Bank to act
firmly so that the economy is disinflating, even while allowing
the weak economy more time than one would normally allow for it
to reach a comfortable level of inflation.”  Net income at 21 of the 30 companies in the Sensex that
have reported quarterly results exceeded analyst estimates,
according to data compiled by Bloomberg. About 47 percent of the
30 index members missed forecasts in the previous quarter.  To contact the reporter on this story:
